descript.abstract: San Francisco Neighborhoods as designated by the San Francisco Mayor's Office of Neighborhood Services.
descript.purpose: Delineate Neighborhoods in San Francisco for maps, queries and analysis. All boundaries are for the purpose of defining general locations of neighborhoods for the SF FIND application only, and as such they are not "hard" lines of demarcation, and are not intended to be used for any other purposes such as City Planning, Real Estate development, Supervisor Districts or Police Precincts. We have defined as many individual neighborhoods within San Francisco as is practical for this usage, we are confident that all significant neighborhoods have been identified, and that we have a consensus as to their general boundaries.

srcinfo.srccontr:
Tom Schedler
While we have attempted to include both new and historic neighborhoods in our list, we acknowledge that some neighborhood definitions have changed significantly over the years. Many large areas remain as neighborhoods on our list, but have been subdivided into smaller neighborhood areas. For example, the Western Addition historically (after 1906) described most of the area west of Van Ness Avenue, south of California Street, and as far west as Lone Mountain and Golden Gate Park. And while the Western Addition remains as a neighborhood on our list, it has now been subdivided into smaller neighborhoods such as Hayes Valley, Golden Gate Park Panhandle, Lower Pacific Heights & Japantown, Anza Vista, and Cathedral Hill. The South Of Market Area has also been subdivided into smaller neighborhoods such as Rincon Hill, Showplace Square and South Beach. In some cases new, or newer, neighborhoods have displaced some historical neighborhoods, such as Mission Bay displacing China Basin, the Marina displacing Crabville-by-the-Bay, and the northern part of the Bayview district displacing Butchertown. Alternatively, some historical neighborhoods have been reinstated on our list, such as Dogpatch and Mint Hill. There are a few instances where a park, due to its size, has been designated as its own non-residential "neighborhood." These would include Golden Gate Park, Lincoln Park/Ft. Miley, John McLaren Park, Candlestick Point SRA and Lakeshore (Lake Merced Park, SF Zoo, Ft. Funston, etc.). We welcome comments and/or suggestions from our SF FIND users as to their ideas regarding our selection of neighborhoods for this map, but we are unable to respond to individual questions. Send comments and/or suggestions to tom.schedler@sfgov.org.

procstep.procdesc:
The Neighborhood data was created via Tom Schedler's personal knowledge and via Tom snapping neighborhood boundaries to existing city street centerlines, Highway centerlines, park boundaries, shorelines, fences, lot lines, etc.
Boundaries were determined by many factors and methods: city street centers were primarily used, whenever possible; natural borders such as the ocean or bay, hills or valleys; man-made borders such as freeways and highways; borders of parks and other properties not bounded by streets; in rare cases individual property or lot lines were used; easements, right-of-ways, stairways and fence lines; "Entrance Gates" and similar signage, such as those for St. Francis Wood, Ingleside Terraces and Westwood Highlands, were also used to determine neighborhood boundaries.
